  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Federal Criminal Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. State-Level Statutes:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Create criminal penalties for laundering activities\n- Require suspicious transaction reporting\n- Provide mechanisms for investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n\nThe laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income and to track financial transactions that might be related to criminal activities.\n\nPenalties can include substantial fines and imprisonment, with severity depending on the specific circumstances of the offense.",
